/-
We disprove the conjecture that if a subset of reals has no 3-term arithmetic progression, its complement must contain an infinite arithmetic progression. We do this by constructing a Baumgartner set, which is a set that contains no 3-term arithmetic progression but intersects every infinite arithmetic progression. The existence of such a set implies that its complement cannot contain any infinite arithmetic progression. The construction uses a basis of R over Q and lifts a "good sequence" from a countable subspace to the whole space.
-/

